  <Fragment slot="headline">Salary Calculator Guide: Gross Pay vs Net Pay Explained</Fragment>

  <p>Many people know their annual salary but still do not know what they will actually take home each paycheck.</p>
  <p>That is because <strong>gross pay</strong> and <strong>net pay</strong> are not the same. Gross pay is what you earn before deductions. Net pay is what reaches your bank account after taxes and other withholdings.</p>

  <h2>Gross Pay vs Net Pay</h2>
  <p><strong>Gross pay</strong> is your salary or wages before taxes, insurance, retirement contributions, or other deductions.</p>
  <p><strong>Net pay</strong> is your take-home pay after those deductions are removed.</p>

  <h2>Why Your Take-Home Pay Is Lower Than Your Salary</h2>
  <p>Your paycheck may include deductions for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Federal income tax</li>
    <li>State income tax, depending on where you live</li>
    <li>Social Security and Medicare</li>
    <li>Health insurance premiums</li>
    <li>401(k) or other retirement contributions</li>
    <li>Other pre-tax or post-tax benefits</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Simple Example</h2>
  <p>If your annual salary is $75,000, your paycheck is not simply $75,000 divided by 12 or 26. Taxes and payroll deductions change the final number.</p>
  <p>That is why a dedicated <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/salary-calculator"><strong>Salary Calculator</strong></a> is useful. It gives you a more realistic estimate of your actual take-home pay.</p>

  <h2>Pay Frequency Matters</h2>
  <p>Your take-home pay depends partly on how often you are paid: weekly, bi-weekly, semi-monthly, or monthly. The annual total may be the same, but the paycheck amount will differ.</p>

  <h2>Common Reasons People Use a Salary Calculator</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Evaluating a new job offer</li>
    <li>Comparing salaries across states</li>
    <li>Estimating monthly budget capacity</li>
    <li>Understanding 401(k) and insurance deductions</li>
    <li>Checking the difference between gross and net income</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
  <p>Your salary number tells only part of the story. What matters for real-life decisions is your net pay after deductions. That is the number to use for budgeting, saving, and comparing job offers.</p>
